President Uhuru Kenyatta has welcomed resumption of direct flights from Mogadishu in Somalia to Nairobi.The first commercial plane carrying 49 passengers from the Somali capital landing at the Jomo Kenyatta International Airport shortly after 1pm on Wednesday.For the last 10 years, flights from Mogadishu were landing at the Wajir Airport for screening and vetting of passengers before proceeding to Nairobi.Uhuru assured Kenyans that security measures have been put in place to ensure safety of passengers."Before the relaunch of the direct flight, a multi-agency security team travelled to Mogadishu to assess the security situation of the airport. This was followed by the setting up of robust security arrangements at the Mogadishu Aden Adde International Airport to oversee flight routes and departure procedures," Uhuru said.Sources have told the Star the security arrangements include a condition that the Kenya's Military Intelligence Unit be involved in vetting Somalia travellers.The Kenyan military officers are also involved in ground activities, such as fuelling of the planes in Mogadishu, the source said.The relaunch of direct flights between Nairobi and Mogadishu was agreed upon during the bilateral talks between Kenya and Somalia that were led by Uhuru and Somali President Abdullahi Mohamed. The Somali President was on his first state visit to Kenya last week.CSs James Macharia (Transport) and Joseph Nkaissery (Interior) were at hand to receive the first flight, marking the resumption of direct flights from Mogadishu to Nairobi after close to 10 years suspension.Macharia said the historic resumption of direct flights between the two cities signalled a revitalisation of cooperation between the two neighbouring countries, brimming with optimism that it would also enhance trade.&ldquo;For us in the transport sector, we have always been working to boost Nairobi&rsquo;s position as a regional aviation hub,&rdquo; he said.Also present at the airport to receive the inaugural flight from Mogadishu, was acting Somalia Ambassador Mohamed Sheikh.